Secrets, and why environment variables are not secret.

There is a pattern in every tutorial, passing a password to a container through an environment variable. It is convenient, and it is not secret. That password leaks in at least four places. It shows up when you inspect the container, where anyone with daemon access can read the environment block. It is exposed in the process environment on the host to anyone who can read it. It sits in the shell history of whoever launched it. And it ends up in crash dumps and in log statements that helpfully include the environment at the time of a crash. On top of that, environment variables are inherited by child processes, so every shell-out inside the container sees the password too.

The proper, container-native approach is a secret file mounted at a known path, readable only by the app's user, with the app reading from that file rather than from the environment. There are three places these come from in the docker ecosystem. Compose secrets define a secret from a file and mount it into the container at a runtime path with restrictive permissions. Swarm secrets, in notebook nine, use the same syntax but go further, encrypting the secret at rest and distributing it only to the nodes that actually need it. And build-kit secret mounts handle secrets needed during a build, like a registry token, mounting them for the duration of a single build step so they never get committed into an image layer, which is exactly what makes them safer than passing a secret as a build argument or environment value that would be baked into the image history.

For production, teams often go one step further and keep the secret out of any file on the deploy host entirely, having the container fetch it at startup from a dedicated secret manager, with a small helper writing it to an in-memory mount for the app to read. That is outside docker's own scope, but it is worth knowing the option exists, because it removes the secret from disk altogether.
